list.description: Bakarwadi is a famous snack from the state of Maharashtra, India. It is had commonly with tea during evenings or late afternoons. It is a savory filling rolled into chickpea dough sliced and deep-fried. Besides being a tea time treat, the spicy and crisp bakarwadi is also specially made during the festival of Diwali.

Bebinca, also known as bibik or bebinka, is a type of pudding and a traditional Goan, East Indian and Mangalorean dessert. Traditional Bebinca has 16 layers. The ingredients include plain flour, sugar, ghee (clarified butter), egg yolk, coconut milk and almond slivers to garnish. It is also a common dessert in Goan restaurants, and a few outlets in Mumbai and Manglore. Bebinca is served warm with cold ice cream. It is also easily available to carry and preserve for a long time or eaten fresh.

Home to the Charminar and glossy pearls, Hyderabad brings to mind delicious flavours that have a Mughal influence, but let us tell you that this city has more to boast about than just biryani. Take for instance, the soft, fluffy biscuits that dissolve in your mouth after a mere bite. The legendary Karachi biscuits hit the spot with their perfect texture and buttery goodness, imbued with tutti-fruity bits and dry fruits that tickle your sweet tooth with every bite. All egg-less and Shelf Life 4 months.

Nestled amidst the Nilgiris is the beautiful town of Ooty, which has an equally beautiful way of making chocolates. There are enough and more reasons to love chocolates and more so if they are homemade. Ooty homemade chocolates entered the market over a decade ago and since then have won over the hearts of children and adults alike. Tantalizingly delicious and aromatic, these melt-in-the-mouth chocolates offer a unique taste without the use of preservatives and synthetic substances. There are a few shops that promise you the taste of authentic Ooty chocolates. As expected, the chocolates are a hit during the valentine season and also used as festive gifts for family and friends. Packaged in tiny pouches and decorative boxes, the chocolates have a good shelf life when refrigerated.

If you want to feel royal, this delicacy is completely for you. Originally prepared in the royal kitchen of Mysore Palace during the regime of Krishnaraja Wadiyar IV, it stole the hearts of the royals then, and now continues to rule over the heart and palate of every person possible. This dish is prepared by adding generous amounts of ghee, sugar and gram.

Kaju Katli is the most sought after sweet made with cashew nuts. One of the most famous Indian sweets, this diamond-shaped treat is sure to delight Kaju, which translates to cashew in Hindi, is the base for this popular delicacy. Firm in texture, yet creamy in taste, Kaju Katli has a nutty flavor that will keep you coming back for more.

Kothmir Marcha (Coriander Chilly) is made up of best quality Coriander and Chilly. Kothmir Marcha are one of the basic ingredients in the Indian cuisine.

Be it the largest world gathering in the world, the Kumbhmela, or be it the food that is made and served with love and hospitality, Nashik, the temple city, wins the heart of all those who flock to visit. One thing that catches the attention of one and all is the hoard of hawkers tossing Nashik''s famous tangy and lemony snack, the chivda. The hot and sweet crunchy mixture of roasted poha, roasted gram, groundnuts, dried coconut, kokum, fried onion, garlic and chilli best when garnished with a squeeze of lemon and a sprinkling of chopped coriander is a sure-shot tongue teaser. 
An all-season favourite, Nashik Chivda makes for a healthy snack and has a shelf life of over a month if preserved in airtight containers. The question is, won''t you finish it before then?

The Taj Mahal is not the only thing in Agra that makes an indelible impression in our hearts. The petha from Agra has also found admirers from across India and the world. The Agra Petha started its journey from the Mughal kitchens to become the most popular dessert of Agra. After all, an array of juicy, melt-in-your-mouth chunks of translucent white pumpkin dipped in sugar syrup are a temptation no one can resist. While the wonders of the petha originated 350 years ago.
Agra Petha is not only a sweet treat for oneself, but also an ideal gift for friends and relatives, especially during the festivals—be it Holi or Diwali. With endless flavours, each more irresistible than the other, like the Angoori, Kesar, Chocolate, Cherry and more, spreading joy with the Agra Petha is now just a click away! 
Agra Petha can be stored for 7-15 days, provided it is refrigerated.

Peda is a sweet from the Indian subcontinent, usually prepared in thick, semi-soft pieces. The main ingredients are khoa, sugar and traditional flavorings, including cardamom seeds, pistachio nuts and saffron. The colour varies from a creamy white to a caramel colour. The word pera is also generically used to mean a blob of any doughy substance, such as flour or khoa.

With each by lane and every area that is known for some specialty or another, Mumbai is a smorgasbord for the food connoisseur. Some things however are still a best-kept secret, and from our culinary diaries, we present one such gem—Mohanlal S Mithaiwala and its famous Ice Halwa. No, it's not frozen like its name suggests, but it does melt in your mouth! Thin rectangular slices of rava held together with milk and ghee and adorned with chopped almonds, pistachio and a trickle of rose water, the Ice Halwa is simply irresistible.
We source it from its original manufacturer that pays as much attention to quality as it does to technology and modern packaging. A popular gift for Diwali, Ganesh Chathurthi or Eid, Ice Halwa also acts the perfect “ice” breaker on Valentine's Day.

Spicy, tangy and crunchy?Sev Namkeen epitomizes the in-between snack in the Indian subcontinent, loved by children and elders alike. The sev that touches the heart however comes straight from the heart of India, Ratlami Sev Namkeen from Madhya Pradesh. Its place of origin, Ratlam, gives this sev its unique taste and of course, its name. This Malwa region is so popular for its sev that 60 manufacturers from Ratlam have together filed for GI (Geographical Indication) certification for their sev to ensure authenticity. The crunchy twisties, made from gram flour and a lot of spices, are an important part of festive gifting and late night hunger pangs, especially during the winters. The best part about this highly addictive namkeen is its non-staining quality as it is fried in sesame oil as well as its long-lasting nature. So go ahead and order some sev to compliment your evening chai or coffee or even those long conversations with old friends!

The Kunda is the most sought-after sweet delicacy in Belgaum.
Belgaum is the city of foodies with cross-culture food and hospitality.The food delicacies and recipes cross both land and water barriers and one can pick his choicest dish from a host of menu, from ethnic North Karnataka stuff to the Marathas, the Sauji, the Konkan, the Gujarati, the Goan, the North Indian, the Punjabi and of course, the Chinese.But, when it comes to sweets, the menu is not complete without the “Kunda” — a name synonymous with Belgaum.

Now, the delicious Kunda is also available in Ready to Eat packs, hygienically packed in retort pouch with shelf life of 6 months.
